node.text:
The Paganism in Portugal...!!!

Europe, which now follows Christianity and hosts the various main sites of Christianity including the Vatican City in Italy, was once a polytheism followers from Romans, Greeks, Pre-Romans and Mithraism... 

Portugal, one of the country of Europe continent, was also once a pagan country which had many gods to worship... Such gods were then taken by Romans and Greeks mythology in their religion and after Christianity, all such places and gods became irrelevant... 

The above pic is alleged to be of the place of worship of Endovelicus, which was the god of Underworld, wealth and afterlife in Iberian Peninsula, which was later incorporated in Romans mythology as Pluto or Serapis... 

Note: The above data is not accurate due to loss of language of Pre-Roman Portugal, data is completely based on Roman and Greeks historians of the region... 

For more such contents, 
Take a look at: @pranjaladitya108 
#SanatanShines

node.text: Hattusa, also known as Hattusha, is an ancient city located near modern Boğazkale in the Çorum Province of Turkey’s Black Sea Region. This ancient city once served as the capital of the Hittite Empire, one of the superpowers of the ancient world. In the Amarna Letters, which have been dated to the 14th century BC, the Hittites were referred to by the Egyptians as a major power, alongside Assyria, Mitanni, and Babylonia, and they were treated as equals. Hattusa was established by the Hatti, the indigenous people who were living in that area prior to the coming of the Hittites. The origins of the Hittites are still a mystery, and they may have invaded / immigrated into Hatti territory, settled, and established their empire there. https://www.ancient-origins.net/ancient-places-asia/hattusa-cursed-city-hatti-and-hittite-empire-005670

node.text: The invention of writing in approximately 3300 B.C. was one of many developments in administrative technology--including the use of geometric tokens for counting and cylinder seals to guarantee transactions--that accompanied the growth of the first cities and states in southern Mesopotamia. This clay tablets fragment contains part of the ancient Akkadian flood story, often called Atra-hasis. The epic tells of how the gods created humans to alleviate their own work, grew tired of the noise of the peoples on earth, and sent various natural disasters – including a flood – to destroy the human race. Because the story describes the intervention of a god to save one man (Atra-hasis) by giving him instruction for building a boat, it is often compared to the biblical story of Noah. The text on this tablet, which reads left to right, describes the noise on earth that led to the gods’ decision to destroy humanity on the front. On the reverse, the very end of the story appears – the gods promise to never send another flood, allowing people to "last forever" – as well as the name of the Mesopotamian flood survivor, who in this text is given the name Ut-napishtim. The epic is best-known from copies of the text dating to the Old Babylonian period, but several examples, including this text, show that the story continued to be copied in later periods. https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/321999

The US returning to Iraq treasure trove of antiquities: Baghdad. The United States will return to Iraq some 17,000 archaeological treasures dating back 4,000 years and looted in recent decades, "unprecedented" restitution, the culture minister in Baghdad said on Wednesday.
Iraqi Prime Minister Mustafa al Kadhemi was set to take back the artifacts from ancient Mesopotamia on his aircraft when he returns on Thursday from Washington where he met US President Joe Biden.
"This is the largest return of antiquities to Iraq, the result of months of efforts by the Iraqi authorities in conjunction with their embassy in Washington".
Most of the ancient pieces document "the commercial exchanges during the Sumerian period"
Among the pieces to be returned to Iraq is a 3,500-year-old clay tablet with a sequence from the epic of Gilgamesh, which once sat in Washington's Museum of the Bible, the US Department of Justice said separately in Washington. It was not immediately clear whether the "Gilgamesh Dream Tablet" would be among the 17,000 pieces to be returned

node.text:
Hire Benakal is a megalithic site in the state of Karnataka, India. It is among a few Indian megalithic sites dated 800 BCE to 200 BCE which are located 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) west of Gangavati town in Koppal district and 35 kilometres (22 mi) from Hospet city. Hire Benakal was built more than 2000 years ago and is reported to be the largest necropolis among the 2000 odd megalithic sites found in South India, mostly in Karnataka. 

In Hire Benkal, the 400-odd funerary monuments are located on a rocky range of seven hillocks. These seven hills are locally in the Kannada language known as elu guddagalu (seven hills). They belong to the transition period between Neolithic age and Iron age. The megaliths, oriented east-west cover an area of nearly 3 km. They are clustered into three groups, each separated by about 200 metres. Together, they cover a distance of nearly a kilometre. 

There are different types of megalithic monuments at Hire Benakal, making it virtually a museum of megalith forms. Several are dolmens– 3 sided chambers with or without portholes (15-18 cm in diameter) and with large stone slabs called capstones forming their roofs. Buried and semi-buried dolmens called cists and dolmenoid cists are sometimes found arranged in circles. Other structures are irregular polygonal chambers and rock shelter chambers.

Hire Benakal also has rock arts that date back to Neolithic times. Based on the typologies and technologies used, researchers has dated these megaliths between 800 BC to 200 BC. Walking among these structures, one gets the eerie feeling of being in a ghost town of abandoned houses. Moriyara Mane (houses of the dwarves) is what the local residents of Hire Benakal call these, and the hill with the megaliths is Moriyara Gudda (hill of the dwarves).

Locals believes that these structures were the houses of an extinct dwarf race called the Moriyas who were endowed with superhuman strength to split and heft heavy stone slabs to erect them. Since 1955, it has been under the management of the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI). Hire Benakal has been recognized as an UNESCO World Heritage Site tentative list on 19th may 2021.
